Qualcomm has revealed its new mid-tier Snapdragon 660 and 630 mobile platforms. The chips feature improved connectivity and better imaging, in addition to more powerful processors. Both system-on-chip (SoC) products provide 4K video capture and playback support, and are manufactured on a 14nm FinFet process node. The new SoCs also include support for up to 8GB of RAM and the Vulkan API. The chips will allow cheaper smartphones to feature improved specifications and features, including better cameras, more memory, fast charging, and Bluetooth 5 support. Qualcomm said its Snapdragon 660 SoC should appear in mobile devices in the second quarter of 2017, while the 630 is expected to launch in the third quarter.